    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Judges and Politics</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Judge Avern Cohn letter on effort to remove politics from judicial races (Oct 23 news article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Bipartisan Effort to Remove Politics From Judicial Races'' (news article, Oct. 23):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Bipartisan Effort to Remove Politics From Judicial Races'' (news article, Oct. 23):</p>
        <p>The effort to remove politics from judicial races by the Constitution Project will get nowhere without legislation. The most egregious conduct in such races is not candidate conduct but rather the spending of enormous amounts of money by special interest groups, sometimes under the guise of issue advocacy, in support of candidates compatible with their views on how cases should be decided.</p>
        <p>The activities of Citizens for  a Strong Ohio, a group supporting  a Republican judge in Ohio's Supreme Court races, for example, will likely not be inhibited, however pure the conduct of the candidate it supports, short of constitutionally enforceable rules.</p>
        <p>AVERN COHN  Detroit, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a federal judge in Detroit.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
